So without further ado, I turn things over to our moderator, Bob Frank.

09:29.080 --> 09:42.240
Thank you very much, Bob.

09:42.240 --> 09:45.240
It's a real treat to be able to participate in a forum like this.

09:45.240 --> 09:50.240
I've been here once before to a forum in this room.

09:50.240 --> 09:52.040
And it's not like the forums that you see on the Sunday news shows or other popular forums

09:52.040 --> 09:53.400
where people shout at each other.

09:53.400 --> 09:58.600
I think here there's an audience that's intelligent enough to tell a good argument from a bad

09:58.600 --> 10:03.480
argument and so the speakers are under some pressure, not saying things that are demonstrably

10:03.480 --> 10:04.480
false.

10:04.480 --> 10:10.040
And there are issues that are required to reach agreement on and I think when you're

10:10.040 --> 10:15.880
ever in a forum like this, it's good to steer clear of most of those issues.

10:15.880 --> 10:22.200
So there's no way you could have a discussion about what the right public policy posture

10:22.200 --> 10:25.160
is on issues like abortion or other things.

10:25.160 --> 10:28.680
You couldn't get agreement in a diverse group on issues like that.

10:28.680 --> 10:34.040
But I think there are many things that we quarrel about where intelligent people could

10:34.040 --> 10:38.320
listen to a discussion of the pros and cons on each side and come away with a clear sense

10:38.320 --> 10:40.400
that there was a right answer.

10:40.400 --> 10:46.760
And so it's always been my inclination in events like these to stick exclusively to the low

10:46.760 --> 10:53.680
hanging fruit, the kinds of things where it is possible to make real headway and debate.

10:53.680 --> 10:58.920
And so I'm not going to say anything at all that any reasonable person could disagree

10:58.920 --> 10:59.920
with.

10:59.920 --> 11:09.360
We'll have a chance to say whether they agree with whether I've done that.

11:09.360 --> 11:16.080
And I'm going to take the, what I think to be the most important issue we face now and

11:16.080 --> 11:20.960
describe how it's not a difficult issue to make genuine progress on.

11:20.960 --> 11:24.200
That's the lingering economic downturn.

11:24.200 --> 11:30.520
It began in 2008 with a financial crisis as always happens in financial crises.

11:30.520 --> 11:36.320
It takes a long time to work off over hanging debt and get the economy back spending.

11:36.320 --> 11:42.320
Again, we're in the midst of what remains a classic demand shortfall downturn.

11:42.320 --> 11:47.280
There's not enough spending to put everyone to work who wants to work.

11:47.280 --> 11:52.560
If you took an economics course long ago, you'll remember the famous national income

11:52.560 --> 11:57.640
identities Y equals C plus I plus G. Why that's national income?

11:57.640 --> 11:59.320
C, that's consumption.

11:59.320 --> 12:03.560
Consumption has been very sluggish because consumers are still paying down debt.

12:03.560 --> 12:06.720
They've made some progress, but it's still a long way to go.

12:06.720 --> 12:10.600
Many of them have remained jobless or are fearful that they'll lose their jobs.

12:10.600 --> 12:14.000
They're not going to spend us out of the downturn.

12:14.000 --> 12:17.720
Businesses, we've all read, are sitting on mountains of cash.

12:17.720 --> 12:19.040
Why aren't they investing?

12:19.040 --> 12:22.200
Some say it's because of uncertainty in the environment.

12:22.200 --> 12:26.600
Maybe that plays some role, but far more important than that is the fact that they already have

12:26.600 --> 12:31.840
facilities that are more than adequate to produce what people want to buy today at the

12:31.840 --> 12:33.760
depressed demand levels.

12:33.760 --> 12:37.800
If there were demand for more output, they would build bigger factories and hire more

12:37.800 --> 12:40.160
workers, but there's not, and so they don't.

12:40.160 --> 12:43.520
So C plus I, those two aren't going anywhere.

12:43.520 --> 12:49.680
Because that leave, as Keynes was the first to point out clearly in a downturn like this,

12:49.680 --> 12:52.640
the solution is for G to get bigger.

12:52.640 --> 12:57.880
People will say we tried G with the stimulus package and it didn't work, so that puts

12:57.880 --> 12:59.640
rest to that lie.

12:59.640 --> 13:05.560
Well, at the time, we were confronting the steepest downturn in employment and output

13:05.560 --> 13:11.440
that we'd seen even through the early months of the Great Depression, output and employment

13:11.440 --> 13:13.760
were falling faster during this financial crisis.

13:13.760 --> 13:18.840
The demand shortfall was something like $2 trillion per year.

13:18.840 --> 13:26.560
It was met by a stimulus program whose total outlays were slated to be $787 billion, about

13:26.560 --> 13:29.120
one third or so of the demand shortfall.

13:29.120 --> 13:33.240
And that was a $2 trillion year shortfall, and the stimulus was spread out over three

13:33.240 --> 13:34.240
years.

13:34.240 --> 13:40.520
It wasn't an ideally constructed stimulus package as the people who are skeptical about government

13:40.520 --> 13:47.000
will give us reason to remember anytime you send the legislative body into a room to make

13:47.000 --> 13:51.240
a bill, all sorts of bad things happen along with whatever good things might happen in

13:51.240 --> 13:52.240
the process.

13:52.240 --> 13:58.040
So the stimulus wasn't up to the task, but studies of it have shown it did some good.

13:58.040 --> 13:59.040
What should we do now?

13:59.040 --> 14:02.680
I say stop arguing about whether stimulus makes sense.

14:02.680 --> 14:06.680
That's an abstract argument that can play out in the economics journals.

14:06.680 --> 14:12.360
I think it will be resolved in favor of the stimulus approach, but in the meantime, I'm

14:12.360 --> 14:16.240
going to make a proposal that I made in a debate I had with P.J.O.

14:16.240 --> 14:19.000
Rourke last fall.

14:19.000 --> 14:23.680
He and I met at the Cornell Club to discuss what should we do about the ailing economy.

14:23.680 --> 14:28.480
He wasn't inclined at the outset to agree with anything I might say on that subject,

14:28.480 --> 14:34.760
but at the end of the session, we went and did a radio interview together and pushed

14:34.760 --> 14:39.640
a common set of proposals which we then elaborated in an op-ed we published a month later.

14:39.640 --> 14:45.200
So let me just say what the solution is that I think every reasonable person ought to be

14:45.200 --> 14:46.200
able to embrace.

14:46.200 --> 14:51.640
And that is we've got the American Society of Civil Engineers report card on America

14:51.640 --> 14:53.520
sitting in front of us.

14:53.520 --> 14:59.360
They've identified $2 trillion worth of desperately overdue maintenance projects in the national

14:59.360 --> 15:01.120
infrastructure sphere.

15:01.120 --> 15:05.360
Now you could say they're engineers, they're just trying to drum up business for themselves,

15:05.360 --> 15:06.760
a fair point.

15:06.760 --> 15:11.200
But as anyone who's driven around New York in a test from firsthand experience, there

15:11.200 --> 15:16.480
is really quite a big inventory of unmet infrastructure repair around the country.

15:16.480 --> 15:21.480
Manhattan dumped how many hundreds of millions of gallons of raw sewage into the East River

15:21.480 --> 15:22.480
last summer.

15:22.480 --> 15:25.920
There are systems failing all around the country.

15:25.920 --> 15:31.400
If we want to rebuild infrastructure, there's never going to be a time cheaper to do it than

15:31.400 --> 15:32.400
now.

15:32.400 --> 15:38.680
The Department of Transportation Nevada identified a 10-mile stretch of Interstate 80 in that

15:38.680 --> 15:41.240
state that could be brought up to speed today.

15:41.240 --> 15:42.680
It's very badly tattered.

15:42.680 --> 15:46.920
It could be brought up to speed today for $6 million outlay.

15:46.920 --> 15:48.280
That's for the 10-mile stretch.

15:48.280 --> 15:54.160
If we wait two years they estimated the repairs, the same repairs, will cost $30 million.

15:54.160 --> 15:59.680
Not taking into account any of the temporary shortfall in demand that we're facing.

15:59.680 --> 16:04.280
Just because the roadbed would get more heavily disrupted and we'd have to dig it out deeper

16:04.280 --> 16:10.080
and the repairs would escalate five-fold with two years' wait.

16:10.080 --> 16:16.520
Throw on top of that the observation that the people who could do those jobs are many of

16:16.520 --> 16:18.720
them sitting idle today.

16:18.720 --> 16:23.720
They would not have to be bid away from other useful tasks as they would be if we wait until

16:23.720 --> 16:28.440
the economy is back on its feet before we attend to that.

16:28.440 --> 16:33.560
There's equipment that is needed to do those jobs sitting idle in the yards.

16:33.560 --> 16:38.680
Materials are cheap now in world markets because the whole world is in a downturn still.

16:38.680 --> 16:42.440
The interest rates on the money needed to finance these projects have never been lower

16:42.440 --> 16:43.840
than they are right now.

16:43.840 --> 16:46.720
If we wait, all those costs are going to go up.

16:46.720 --> 16:48.720
The capital dome is crumbling.

16:48.720 --> 16:54.520
The Northeast rail corridor desperately needs capital improvements.

16:54.520 --> 16:56.440
When is the time to do that?

16:56.440 --> 16:58.000
Right now is the time to do that.

16:58.000 --> 16:59.680
That would increase spending.

16:59.680 --> 17:03.760
It would put money into the hands of people who would go out and spend it on other things

17:03.760 --> 17:05.360
and it would begin to circulate.

17:05.360 --> 17:07.480
That's the traditional stimulus problem.

17:07.480 --> 17:12.120
But even if it did none of those things, we would get jobs done that need to be done

17:12.120 --> 17:15.960
at a fraction of the cost that will end up incurring if we have to wait.

17:15.960 --> 17:18.680
So, again, that's what I see as the most important thing.

17:18.680 --> 17:21.160
The most important and pressing problem.

17:21.160 --> 17:26.600
I think there's an easy way to make progress on that problem that all people of goodwill

17:26.600 --> 17:28.000
ought to be able to agree on.

17:28.000 --> 17:34.640
What PJ O'Rourke and I recommended was send a bipartisan commission into a room with a

17:34.640 --> 17:40.720
report card on the American infrastructure and allow them to identify which project should

17:40.720 --> 17:44.040
not be funded for immediate green light.

17:44.040 --> 17:48.320
All others get the green light and we start work on them right away.

17:48.320 --> 17:52.640
If people want to object, we can't borrow more money to finance more government spending.

17:52.640 --> 17:56.640
The debt is already crippling our grandchildren.

17:56.640 --> 18:00.640
That's an incoherent objection if you think about it more carefully.

18:00.640 --> 18:05.840
Think about a family trying to decide whether to put insulation in its attic because energy

18:05.840 --> 18:08.160
prices went up.

18:08.160 --> 18:10.400
It's going to have to borrow money to do that.

18:10.400 --> 18:13.600
We'll have to go into debt further than it's already in debt.

18:13.600 --> 18:15.160
Should it do it?

18:15.160 --> 18:21.000
Answer the question, can't be determined without looking at the logic of the investment.

18:21.000 --> 18:25.680
If the investment is going to cost 50 a month to pay off the loan for doing the work and

18:25.680 --> 18:30.880
it's going to reduce their utilities bill by 100 a month, there's no cogent argument

18:30.880 --> 18:33.800
against doing that investment right away.

18:33.800 --> 18:35.800
And the sooner you do it, the better.

18:35.800 --> 18:40.560
That's the situation we're in with infrastructure and we could get the economy back on its feet

18:40.560 --> 18:41.720
in a hurry.

18:41.720 --> 18:45.360
Once we get the economy back on its feet, we'll have to worry about what to do about budget

18:45.360 --> 18:50.240
deficits which are truly an important long run problem, what to do about health care

18:50.240 --> 18:55.480
costs which are a big important part of that problem and a host of other things will get

18:55.480 --> 18:59.800
into that as the panel unfolds.

18:59.800 --> 19:06.840
That's my claim about what we could do now that no reasonable person should object to.

19:06.840 --> 19:08.680
And let me just invite.

19:08.680 --> 19:12.720
In a clockwise fashion, Jeffrey, do you want to take first crack at all there?

19:12.720 --> 19:17.200
Okay, so I'm not going to come back to your specific remarks in a second.

19:17.200 --> 19:21.480
The question that was posed was why do economists disagree and just to prove that economists

19:21.480 --> 19:27.360
are truly disagreeable, I'm going to disagree with the proposition that economists disagree.

19:27.360 --> 19:32.040
Of course they do disagree, but I want to argue that in an important sense, they agree

19:32.040 --> 19:36.160
and they agree way more than many other disciplines.

19:36.160 --> 19:39.400
What they agree upon is a methodology.

19:39.400 --> 19:44.440
Economists, across political perspectives, across which school they were trained at or

19:44.440 --> 19:50.760
whatever, they agree that we should have models that are mainly mathematical models sometimes

19:50.760 --> 19:55.680
are written down in words but could be written in mathematical equations, that we should

19:55.680 --> 20:01.840
think about those models as generating testable hypotheses, meaning statements about the world

20:01.840 --> 20:06.400
or forecasts about the world that one could examine with data and in principle, if you

20:06.400 --> 20:13.160
had the right kind of data, either reject or fail to reject and so, like any science,

20:13.160 --> 20:17.480
we would be able to see which models, which hypotheses about the world seemed to fit the

20:17.480 --> 20:19.600
world and which one didn't.

20:19.600 --> 20:26.440
Now of course, you should say to me, if all economists agree with that, then how come there's

20:26.440 --> 20:32.000
so much disagreement about many things, including relatively technical factual type things,

20:32.000 --> 20:35.000
why because we can't do controlled experiments for the most part?

20:35.000 --> 20:39.080
Now there is a branch of economics that does a lot of experiments, hey, I'm going to leave

20:39.080 --> 20:43.920
that aside because they're not quite experiments in the same sense as a biologist can do an

20:43.920 --> 20:47.560
experiment on whether watering plants helps them grow or not.

20:47.560 --> 20:52.440
When economists experiment on people, they know they're being experimented on and that

20:52.440 --> 20:54.880
might affect the outcome to the experiments.

20:54.880 --> 20:59.880
For a whole bunch of things we care about, such as the stimulus, it is impossible to do

20:59.880 --> 21:02.880
a real double blind placebo controlled experiment.

21:02.880 --> 21:07.880
We don't have a parallel universe in which Ben Bernanke did not increase the money stock

21:07.880 --> 21:12.880
or in which the Obama administration did not propose a stimulus, so we can't really know

21:12.880 --> 21:17.280
whether the Keynesian model is accurate or not or to what parts of it are accurate and

21:17.280 --> 21:18.280
things like that.

21:18.280 --> 21:21.440
Can historical information help you?

21:21.440 --> 21:27.840
Social episodes are almost always frequently contaminated by the fact that there are many

21:27.840 --> 21:34.800
things going on, some of which we can't control for, and we don't always know which came first

21:34.800 --> 21:40.920
the treatment or the response or the anticipation of the treatment and then the observed response.

21:40.920 --> 21:47.400
So in Professor Frank's example, one issue that comes up is how people respond to the

21:47.400 --> 21:51.520
fiscal cliff and how are people responding to the debt and things stimulus.

21:51.520 --> 21:55.720
If people knew it was coming, they might have changed their behavior before it went into

21:55.720 --> 21:59.000
effect and that makes it harder to draw inferences from the data.

21:59.000 --> 22:05.400
So what we generally try to use is these historical sort of quasi experiments, but they're highly,

22:05.400 --> 22:06.400
highly imperfect.

22:06.400 --> 22:09.760
It's really hard to disentangle the cause from the effect.

22:09.760 --> 22:15.600
So given that if we agree on methodology that says we would like to be able to do experiments,

22:15.600 --> 22:17.960
but we can't do experiments, then what happens?

22:17.960 --> 22:20.920
Then I think two really important things take over.

22:20.920 --> 22:26.080
First of all, economists, because they're people, have very different views about efficiency

22:26.080 --> 22:28.480
versus redistribution.

22:28.480 --> 22:33.480
If you can make economists across any political persuasion answer questions in a very specific

22:33.480 --> 22:39.880
way and say which of these two policies is likely to increase the size of the pie, I

22:39.880 --> 22:41.440
think you will get a lot of agreement.

22:41.440 --> 22:47.000
So in a textbook, in a setting of an academic paper, in a seminar room, there's not so much

22:47.000 --> 22:52.520
disagreement on how the model would work, what effect will have on who gets to eat the pie

22:52.520 --> 22:57.720
versus how big the pie is, but different economists have very different views on whether they

22:57.720 --> 23:03.200
think policy should emphasize making the pie bigger or trying to get the pie divided up

23:03.200 --> 23:05.720
in a fashion that's regarded as fair.

23:05.720 --> 23:09.760
Secondly, an auxiliary problem is economists disagree a lot or they just don't really

23:09.760 --> 23:15.360
know because we have even less evidence on which policies will end up being implemented

23:15.360 --> 23:18.480
by the political process in a successful way.

23:18.480 --> 23:23.520
So say in the setting of global warming, economists might tend to agree that the ideal policy

23:23.520 --> 23:28.800
is a harmonized global carbon tax, and yet they know that it's not likely that we're

23:28.800 --> 23:32.080
going to end up with a global harmonized carbon tax.

23:32.080 --> 23:37.360
And so then you're asking, well, which of the imperfect policy responses to global warming

23:37.360 --> 23:42.200
some kinds of cap and trade or Kyoto protocols or certain types of regulation on the use of

23:42.200 --> 23:46.880
carbon-based energy, which of those will get us closer to a decent policy, that depends

23:46.880 --> 23:51.040
on awful lot on politics and economists don't know much about that at all.

23:51.040 --> 23:54.800
So I think we do agree on a methodology.

23:54.800 --> 23:59.280
We disagree because we're people and we put different weights on the objectives of policy

23:59.280 --> 24:03.480
and we have different understandings about how to get particular policies to actually

24:03.480 --> 24:06.080
be adopted and implemented.

24:06.080 --> 24:13.360
So just really quickly, I'll just leave it a sentence or two for now, I disagree with

24:13.360 --> 24:18.760
some parts of what Bob said about the stimulus and about doing lots of civil engineering

24:18.760 --> 24:23.200
projects, except that if you think of the way I think about it, he basically said we

24:23.200 --> 24:30.000
should use cost-benefit analysis to decide what transportation projects we should do.

24:30.000 --> 24:35.640
If that's exactly the way the stimulus had been done, I would have been 100% but I think

24:35.640 --> 24:41.360
large parts of it did not satisfy the reasonable cost-benefit standards.

24:41.360 --> 24:42.360
Joseph?

24:42.360 --> 24:48.880
Okay, I want to follow up on something Jeff said and that is why do economists disagree?

24:48.880 --> 24:52.640
Miller Freeman gave an answer to that a long time ago when he said, well, economists don't

24:52.640 --> 24:54.200
want to disagree on ends.

24:54.200 --> 24:56.160
Everybody's in favor of prosperity.

24:56.160 --> 24:58.880
Most people accept the worst misanthropes.

24:58.880 --> 25:03.240
But we disagree about the means and the means are basically the different theories that

25:03.240 --> 25:08.840
you use to implement ways to achieve prosperity and stability and supposedly all these ends

25:08.840 --> 25:12.040
that we will agree on.

25:12.040 --> 25:13.160
I used to believe that.

25:13.160 --> 25:15.400
I don't really believe that much anymore.

25:15.400 --> 25:21.960
What I think is that we also disagree on ends, very, very deeply disagree on ends.

25:21.960 --> 25:27.960
Because once you begin to prescribe policies, tax increases would be good, you've stepped

25:27.960 --> 25:30.440
outside your role as an economist.

25:30.440 --> 25:36.280
You can describe what would happen if you increase the tax and you can disagree on that

25:36.280 --> 25:37.280
with other economists.

25:37.280 --> 25:40.960
But once you say that, I think it's good and therefore we should implement it, you are

25:40.960 --> 25:42.960
then making a value judgment.

25:42.960 --> 25:46.960
Economics, just like medicine, is a value-free subject.

25:46.960 --> 25:52.960
So a doctor can say, the point of competence of a physician is to say, well, if you put

25:52.960 --> 25:57.800
arsenic in that person's drink, then that person will, certain bodily functions will

25:57.800 --> 26:00.400
cease and that person will die.

26:00.400 --> 26:05.600
If the physician goes beyond that and says something like, and that's murder and you

26:05.600 --> 26:08.760
shouldn't do that, well, he's no longer speaking as a physician.

26:08.760 --> 26:12.240
He's speaking as a citizen with a certain scale of values.

26:12.240 --> 26:16.520
And there might be someone that wants to kill Hitler or kill a dictator.

26:16.520 --> 26:19.720
And so we don't really agree on the ends.

26:19.720 --> 26:23.400
And that's the point I would like to make.

26:23.400 --> 26:30.400
For example, I don't think a dollar spent by government on its favorite interests or bailing

26:30.400 --> 26:35.240
out big corporations and especially financial institutions, I don't think that's equal to

26:35.240 --> 26:39.400
a dollar spent by a family who earns the money.

26:39.400 --> 26:43.760
In other words, I want to make a distinction between taxpayers, people who produce and

26:43.760 --> 26:47.280
earn through exchange on the market, and tax consumers.

26:47.280 --> 26:52.320
That distinction was made a long time ago by a political theorist, John C. Calhoun.

26:52.320 --> 26:56.200
And what Calhoun said was, look, society, the only two classes in society, forget about

26:56.200 --> 27:00.320
men and women, blacks and whites, gays and straits, the only two real classes that you

27:00.320 --> 27:06.740
see in every society throughout history are the tax consumers, those that live by either

27:06.740 --> 27:11.840
taxing without giving something in exchange or printing money, and those who live by the

27:11.840 --> 27:13.600
sweat of their brow.

27:13.600 --> 27:22.320
So I look at the economy as in class conflict from the beginning to its very, very depths

27:22.320 --> 27:28.800
between those who live through government and those who live by earning, by producing

27:28.800 --> 27:33.520
what consumers desire, whether or not an outsider, like myself or Bob, likes what's being produced

27:33.520 --> 27:38.000
by the market, whether it's pornography or Beethoven concertos.

27:38.000 --> 27:40.000
That's besides the point.

27:40.000 --> 27:44.400
So just to get to Bob's point, I do want to say that I disagree that there's a spending

27:44.400 --> 27:45.880
shortfall.

27:45.880 --> 27:50.920
I think in fact that what has occurred is that we have a regime uncertainty that is entrepreneurs

27:50.920 --> 27:56.280
after coming off the euphoria of the boom from 2001 to 2005, realize that they were

27:56.280 --> 27:58.280
deeply wrong about things.

27:58.280 --> 28:02.920
Now, the Federal Reserve during that period increased the money supply by officials'

28:02.920 --> 28:08.160
fed statistics at about $1 billion per day for five straight years.

28:08.160 --> 28:10.880
Heat the interest rate down to 1%.

28:10.880 --> 28:17.200
I think this caused tremendous profit and loss miscalculations, caused over development

28:17.200 --> 28:22.560
of certain sectors, housing and so on, and instead of allowing prices to, asset values

28:22.560 --> 28:28.960
to drop, now they pumped up household net worth that is the value of your homes and the value

28:28.960 --> 28:36.640
of your 401ks by $23 trillion, okay, in the course of three years.

28:36.640 --> 28:42.680
Then the crisis struck you had a drop of about $15 trillion in household net worth, which

28:42.680 --> 28:49.560
was equal to the annual GDP of Japan, Great Britain and Germany, instead of allowing asset

28:49.560 --> 28:53.480
prices to adjust, instead of allowing other prices to adjust, other costs and so on to

28:53.480 --> 28:57.640
adjust, in the downward direction, which is what should have happened.

28:57.640 --> 29:04.240
What happened was that we had stimulus and then we had QE1, QE2 and QE infinity now, right?

29:04.240 --> 29:10.000
There's $40 billion every month being pumped in to buy mortgage-backed securities.

29:10.000 --> 29:14.520
I think that is giving pause to entrepreneurship in this country.

29:14.520 --> 29:18.160
They don't know what's going to happen with a fiscal cliff, beyond that is the huge debt

29:18.160 --> 29:25.040
that's going to continue to grow and I think that the uncertainty about Obamacare is something

29:25.040 --> 29:27.280
else that's causing all of this to happen.

29:27.280 --> 29:31.520
If we're really worried about spending and I'll stop after this sentence, let's suspend

29:31.520 --> 29:33.640
the income tax, the personal income tax for one year.

29:33.640 --> 29:35.960
Let's just suspend it.

29:35.960 --> 29:40.240
That was actually put forth by a few economists right after the financial crisis.

29:40.240 --> 29:44.000
I'm all in favor of that, two years.

29:44.000 --> 29:50.080
Then we'll have people with productive saving instead of expanding credit to get more spending.

29:50.080 --> 29:54.400
We'll have productive saving and we'll have consumers, earners, arranging their affairs

29:54.400 --> 29:57.000
in a way that brings them greater satisfaction.

29:57.000 --> 29:59.840
I'll stop there.

29:59.840 --> 30:03.800
It was proposed to eliminate the payroll tax.

30:03.800 --> 30:06.360
Was that a proposal that you favored as well, Joseph?

30:06.360 --> 30:13.840
Well, depending, the income tax brings in between 42 and 47 percent of federal revenues.

30:13.840 --> 30:20.200
The payroll tax may be on a 48 percent, either one is fine for me.

30:20.200 --> 30:25.200
Yeah, it was proposed and defeated in the IRS.

30:25.200 --> 30:32.760
Graciela, did you have an axe to grind in any of this or feel free, obviously, to go

30:32.760 --> 30:40.800
off in your own direction?

30:40.800 --> 30:49.600
First of all, the question that we are meeting here about why economists disagree.

