01:03:18.600 --> 01:03:22.600
Ed questions whether people really have turned away from wanting big things.

01:03:22.600 --> 01:03:29.600
I think the fundamental driver of consumption has been how the income distribution has changed over the last three decades.

01:03:29.600 --> 01:03:38.600
What we saw right after World War II for three decades was pretty uniform growth across all the income classes.

01:03:38.600 --> 01:03:42.600
About 3% a year for rich, middle and low income families alike.

01:03:42.600 --> 01:03:48.600
Since the mid-70s, virtually all the income growth has gone to people at the top of the income letter.

01:03:48.600 --> 01:03:53.600
It's the same pattern within every group. If you look at college graduates, it's the same pattern.

01:03:53.600 --> 01:04:00.600
Those at the bottom aren't doing very well compared to 30 years ago. The ones in the middle have gained a little ground, not much.

01:04:00.600 --> 01:04:08.600
The gains have been the lion's share of them at the top, and if you look at the top 5%, most of the gains there are in the top 1%.

01:04:08.600 --> 01:04:18.600
There the biggest gains have been in the top 1-10th to 1%. So that's the demand shifter that's been going on for 30 years.

01:04:18.600 --> 01:04:23.600
What's happened is that the people who've gotten a lot more money are spending more money.

01:04:23.600 --> 01:04:31.600
That's totally the expected response from people in every income group. You get more money, you build bigger, you buy more expensive.

01:04:31.600 --> 01:04:37.600
What's equally clear is that people in the middle don't seem offended by that.

01:04:37.600 --> 01:04:42.600
They want to see pictures of the yachts and the mansions. They're not shaking their fists in anger.

01:04:42.600 --> 01:04:47.600
They kind of think they'll be rich someday or their kids will be. Let's see what's in store for us.

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:56.600
There's not any case to be made that the public is made indirectly less happy by the spectacle of the rich buying fancy things.

01:04:56.600 --> 01:05:03.600
But here's what has happened. The rich spend more on their daughters' wedding. They spend 2 million, 3 million.

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:08.600
That means the people who are just below the top rung have a new standard.

01:05:08.600 --> 01:05:14.600
They want their daughters' wedding to seem special too, but special is a relative concept, so they spend a little more.

01:05:14.600 --> 01:05:22.600
Now it's cascaded all the way down the income ladder. The average American wedding costs $30,000 in real dollars.

01:05:22.600 --> 01:05:33.600
In 1980 it was $11,000. And no one, I don't think anybody on this panel would be willing to say with a straight face that couples are happier now because their weddings cost three times as much.

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:44.600
It's just that the standards have shifted. Why have they shifted? Because spending at the top went up dramatically and then there's this sort of indirect cascade that ripples throughout the economy.

01:05:44.600 --> 01:05:50.600
And talking about waste, much of that extra spending has been pure wheel spinning.

01:05:50.600 --> 01:05:56.600
Is the CEO happier with a bigger mansion? Why does he need one? It's because other CEOs have a bigger one.

01:05:56.600 --> 01:06:03.600
He didn't and his company would appear to be in jeopardy and he couldn't entertain in the style that was expected.

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:16.600
